---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
import FindingCard from '@/components/FindingCard.astro';
---

<ReportLayout title="Homepage — Myprotein Homepage">

  <section class="report-intro">
    <h1 class="report-h1">UX Audit: Myprotein Homepage</h1>
    <p class="report-meta">Myprotein UK Homepage &mdash; Audited 2 June 2026</p>
    <p class="report-summary">
      Full-page audit of myprotein.com at desktop (1440px) and mobile (390px) viewports during an active
      "Impact Week Sale" promotional period. The page carries a very high promotional load: a hero banner,
      a countdown urgency bar, a Deal of the Day mid-banner, six category quick-links, a "What's New" editorial
      carousel, a Best Sellers product grid, an app download section, and a clothing product grid. Core findings
      centre on promo bar legibility, the absence of a true homepage H1, inconsistent product card treatment,
      and a Quick Buy CTA that deviates from the brand's mint-ring primary button signature.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="findings-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Findings</h2>

    <!-- HIGH PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="Countdown urgency bar text is truncated on desktop — deal conditions hidden"
      viewport="Desktop"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="countdown-truncation"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The orange countdown/urgency bar reads: "UP TO 80% OFF + EXTRA 15% OFF ALL CREATINE SUPPLEMENTS |
        APPLIES AT BASKET | ENDS IN…" — the sentence is cut mid-word at the available width. At 1440px this
        is entirely avoidable. The key qualifying conditions ("applies at basket") are the most legally and
        commercially important part of this message and are partially hidden.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Users who miss "APPLIES AT BASKET" may add to cart expecting a discounted price and be surprised at
        checkout, increasing abandonment at the most critical conversion step. This also carries a potential
        ASA/CAP compliance risk around hidden conditions.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Reduce font size from the current ~12px to 11px, or shorten the copy to "UP TO 80% OFF + EXTRA 15%
        OFF CREATINE — applied at basket. Ends in:" so the full message fits in one line at 1440px.
        Alternatively, break into two lines within the bar. Do not rely on ellipsis for a legally significant message.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="No page H1 — homepage has no semantic heading"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="missing-h1"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        DOM inspection confirms no H1 element exists on the homepage. The hero banner heading ("UP TO 80% OFF
        ALMOST EVERYTHING") is rendered inside an image, not as a text element. There is no programmatic
        page title for screen readers or search engines.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Missing H1 harms SEO (Google uses H1 as a primary relevance signal for homepages) and fails WCAG 2.1
        SC 1.3.1 (Info and Relationships) for screen reader users who rely on heading structure to navigate.
        It also makes the page harder to parse for assistive technology users.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Add a visually hidden H1 such as "Myprotein — No.1 Online Sports Nutrition Brand" immediately after
        the header using a CSS class like <code>.sr-only</code>. Alternatively, extract the hero headline
        from the image and render it as a styled H1 overlay on the banner.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Primary hero CTA 'Shop Now' uses ghost/outline style — low visual weight for a sale hero"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="design"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="hero-cta-weight"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The hero banner "SHOP NOW" button is a ghost/outline style (transparent background, white border) on
        a dark, image-heavy background. Computed styles show <code>background: rgba(0,0,0,0)</code> with a
        white border. At desktop the button is relatively small (approximately 160px wide) against a
        full-bleed 1440px-wide banner.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Ghost CTAs on photographic backgrounds are consistently lower-performing than solid-fill buttons.
        During a high-stakes sale period ("Impact Week"), the primary conversion action needs maximum
        contrast and visual weight. This is the first clickable element a user reaches after the hero,
        and its low contrast reduces click-through.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Switch the hero CTA to a solid-fill button. Given the dark hero background, use the brand's teal
        (<code>#003942</code>) or white (<code>#FFFFFF</code>) fill with the mint ring signature
        (<code>#94E5B5</code> outer ring) that the Quick Buy button uses. Size up to at least 200px
        wide and 48px tall.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <!-- MEDIUM PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="Quick Buy button missing the mint outer ring — brand CTA signature not applied"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="quick-buy-mint-ring"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The Quick Buy button on product cards uses <code>border-radius: 32px</code> and the correct teal
        background (<code>oklch(0.3162 0.055061 211.831)</code> ≈ <code>#003942</code>), but DevTools shows
        <code>box-shadow: none</code> — the mint outer ring (<code>#94E5B5</code>) that is the brand's
        primary CTA signature is absent. The border is set as a 2px solid teal stroke, not a ring.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        The mint ring is a brand-differentiating detail that signals premium quality and brand confidence.
        Its absence means the most frequently seen CTA on the page (Quick Buy appears on every product card)
        doesn't carry the full brand signature, diluting the design system's intended impact.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Add <code>box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px #94E5B5</code> (or the correct token value) to the
        <code>.quick-buy-btn</code> class (or equivalent). Remove the current solid border or keep it
        inside the ring as a separator.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Trust/benefits bar content is too dense and icons are small at desktop"
      viewport="Desktop"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="design"
      ticketable={false}
      findingId="trust-bar-density"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The trust bar beneath the header shows four items inline: "Free standard delivery on £50 spend",
        "Extra 10% off via App", "Earn £15 Credit?", and "Over 210k reviews & 4.4 rated". At 1440px the
        items have generous breathing room, but the icons are very small (~16px) and the text is
        approximately 13px — below the recommended 14px minimum body size.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Trust signals are a key conversion lever on the homepage. If users can't quickly scan and absorb
        them, the signals fail to do their job. Small text also marginally fails WCAG AA at the contrast
        ratios possible with the current colour on light background.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Increase trust bar text to 14px minimum. Scale icons to 20px. Consider bold-weighting the key
        fact in each item (e.g. "£50", "10%", "£15", "210k") to aid quick scanning. The designer should
        spec this before engineering implements.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Product cards have 0px border radius — inconsistent with design system (should be 12px)"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="card-border-radius"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Computed style on product card wrappers (<code>[class*="ProductItem"]</code>) returns
        <code>border-radius: 0px</code>. Per the design system, cards should use 12px border radius.
        Images within cards also have square corners, making the grid look flat and dated compared
        to the rest of the design language.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Inconsistent radius creates a visual hierarchy mismatch — category tiles correctly use 8px radius,
        the Quick Buy button uses 32px, but cards are square. This inconsistency undermines the perception
        of a premium, polished brand.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Apply <code>border-radius: 12px</code> and <code>overflow: hidden</code> to the card wrapper
        element so images inherit the rounding. Verify this is consistent across Best Sellers and
        Trending This Week tabs.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Mobile hero CTA 'Shop Now' is very small — poor tap target"
      viewport="Mobile"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="mobile-hero-tap-target"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        On mobile (390px viewport), the hero "SHOP NOW" button sits low in the fold as the hero image
        crops significantly. The button's visual size appears to be approximately 140px wide and under
        40px tall — below the WCAG recommended 44px minimum tap target height.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Undersized tap targets on the primary conversion action increase misclick rate, particularly on
        smaller phones. This is a direct friction point on the most critical CTA on the page.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Set a minimum <code>height: 48px</code> and <code>min-width: 160px</code> on the hero CTA at
        mobile breakpoints. Ensure adequate padding so the tap area exceeds 44x44px regardless of
        text length.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="'What's New' editorial cards have text overlaid on dark images with marginal contrast"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="design"
      ticketable={false}
      findingId="editorial-overlay-contrast"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The "What's New" carousel shows product/editorial cards where small label text (e.g. "FORM",
        "FUNCTION", "FLATTERING FITS") is overlaid directly on photographic backgrounds. These labels
        appear to be approximately 12–14px, positioned in the lower third of dark images.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Without a guaranteed dark scrim or text shadow behind them, these overlaid labels risk failing
        WCAG AA contrast (4.5:1 for small text) depending on the specific image shown. Photography
        backgrounds vary — what passes on one image may fail on another. This is an ongoing risk
        rather than a single fixable instance.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Add a CSS gradient scrim to the lower portion of all editorial card images:
        <code>background: linear-gradient(to top, rgba(0,0,0,0.65) 0%, rgba(0,0,0,0) 60%)</code>.
        This ensures consistent contrast regardless of image content. Design to spec before engineering implements.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <!-- LOW PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="App download section CTA copy says 'Shop Now' — doesn't match the action"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="low"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="app-cta-mismatch"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The "Download the App" section uses "SHOP NOW" as its CTA label. Clicking it should prompt an
        app store download or redirect to a deep link/app landing page — "Shop Now" describes the wrong
        action and sets incorrect expectations.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Mismatched CTA copy reduces click confidence. Users who want to download the app may overlook
        this CTA entirely if they're scanning for an "install" or "download" affordance.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Change CTA label to "Download the App" or "Get the App" with separate Apple App Store and
        Google Play buttons where feasible. At minimum, rename to "Download Now".
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Mobile navigation collapsed to 3 top-level items — 'Brands' tab is low priority above the fold"
      viewport="Mobile"
      priority="low"
      ticketType="design"
      ticketable={false}
      findingId="mobile-nav-priority"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        On mobile, the sticky nav bar shows three tabs: Nutrition, Clothing, Brands. "Brands" occupies
        a top-level position equal to the primary product categories, but is a lower-intent destination
        for most visitors. The most-used entry points (Protein, Supplements, Vitamins) are one tap deeper.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Top-level navigation real estate on mobile is extremely limited. Giving "Brands" equal billing
        with the core nutrition and clothing journeys may slow users down who are looking for specific
        product categories.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        This requires a navigation architecture decision. Consider whether "Brands" should remain at
        top level or move into the Nutrition/Clothing mega-menus. Needs user research or click data
        to validate before changing.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Design Consistency</h2>
    <p>
      The page uses Figtree correctly as the font family across all inspected elements, and body copy
      is set at 16px which meets minimum legibility standards. The primary colour system is broadly
      coherent: the header background is white, the teal (<code>oklch(0.3162 0.055061 211.831)</code>,
      approximately <code>#003942</code>) is used correctly for Quick Buy buttons and interactive
      controls, and the orange-red (<code>rgb(217, 66, 14)</code>) is appropriately restricted to
      promotional/urgency contexts (countdown bar, category tiles).
    </p>
    <p>
      Key deviations from the design system: (1) Product card border radius is 0px against the specified
      12px. (2) The Quick Buy button lacks the mint outer ring (<code>#94E5B5</code> box-shadow)
      that is the brand's primary CTA signature — <code>box-shadow: none</code> is computed.
      (3) The hero CTA "Shop Now" button uses a ghost style (transparent background) which is not
      the primary button pattern for high-conversion contexts. (4) Category tiles use <code>border-radius: 8px</code>
      which is consistent with the chip/selector token. The countdown bar background
      (<code>rgb(217, 66, 15)</code>) is a 1-unit RGB variant from the tile colour
      (<code>rgb(217, 66, 14)</code>) — this is likely a rounding artefact rather than an intentional
      deviation, but worth locking to a single token value. The Was/Save price badges on product cards
      use coral at 40% opacity (<code>rgba(255, 164, 163, 0.4)</code>) for "Was" and mint at 40% opacity
      (<code>rgba(190, 246, 213, 0.4)</code>) for "Save" — confirmed as intentional design system usage
      of the brand accent colours, applied consistently across all four Best Sellers cards. No issue here.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Accessibility Notes</h2>
    <p>
      The most significant accessibility issue is the absent H1, which fails WCAG 2.1 SC 1.3.1 (Info
      and Relationships) and prevents screen reader users from understanding the page structure via
      heading navigation. The hero banner headline is embedded in an image with no accessible text
      equivalent visible in the DOM, compounding this issue.
    </p>
    <p>
      Trust bar text at approximately 13px is below the recommended 14px minimum and may present
      marginal contrast issues depending on the computed colour against the light background. The
      overlay text on editorial image cards in "What's New" carries ongoing contrast risk without
      a guaranteed scrim. The countdown bar text at 12px is small and uses white on an orange-red
      background (<code>rgb(217, 66, 15)</code>) — while this palette typically passes AA for large
      text, the 12px size means it should be verified with a contrast checker at the exact computed
      values. Mobile tap targets on the hero CTA appear to fall short of the 44x44px WCAG minimum.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Conversion Summary</h2>
    <p>
      The homepage is in "sale mode" and does a reasonable job of communicating the promotional moment
      — the hero is high-impact and the product grid loads with clear pricing including was/save indicators.
      However, the conversion path has several friction points. The hero CTA is a low-weight ghost button
      that undersells the sale urgency. The countdown bar truncates the most important qualifying
      information. Product cards lack border radius, making the grid feel unpolished relative to
      the brand's aspirational positioning. The Quick Buy button — the most direct route from
      browse to basket on the homepage — is missing its mint ring signature, making it feel less
      premium and slightly inconsistent with the rest of the interaction vocabulary.
    </p>
    <p>
      On mobile, the experience is broadly functional: the navigation collapses cleanly to three
      primary tabs, category tiles are well-sized for touch, and the product grid reflows sensibly.
      The main mobile-specific concern is the small hero CTA tap target and the loss of the trust
      bar (only one benefit — "Extra 10% off via App" — is visible in the mobile header, with the
      others de-prioritised).
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Recommended Implementation Order</h2>
    <ol class="recommendations">
      <li>Add a visually hidden H1 to the homepage to fix the semantic heading gap — quick engineering fix, high SEO and accessibility impact.</li>
      <li>Fix countdown urgency bar truncation — shorten copy or reduce font size so the full message, including "APPLIES AT BASKET", is always visible at desktop.</li>
      <li>Apply <code>box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px #94E5B5</code> to Quick Buy buttons to reinstate the brand mint ring CTA signature.</li>
      <li>Apply <code>border-radius: 12px; overflow: hidden</code> to product card wrappers across Best Sellers and Trending grids.</li>
      <li>Increase hero CTA minimum height to 48px on mobile and switch from ghost to solid-fill button style — requires design spec first.</li>
      <li>Rename the App Download section CTA from "Shop Now" to "Download Now" or "Get the App".</li>
      <li>Review editorial card image overlays and add gradient scrims to ensure contrast compliance across variable photography.</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

</ReportLayout>

<style is:global>
  .finding-card code {
    font-family: Menlo, Monaco, 'Courier New', monospace;
    font-size: 12px;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    padding: 1px 5px;
    border-radius: 4px;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
  }
</style>

<style>
  .report-intro { margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .report-h1 { font-size: 26px; font-weight: 800; color: var(--color-text-heading); line-height: 1.25; margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .report-meta { font-size: 13px; color: var(--color-text-body); opacity: 0.65; margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .report-summary { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); max-width: 680px; }
  .findings-section { margin-bottom: 48px; }
  .section-heading { font-size: 18px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-heading); margin-bottom: 20px; padding-bottom: 10px; border-bottom: 2px solid rgba(0, 57, 66, 0.1); }
  .prose-section { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  .prose-section p { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); }
  .recommendations { padding-left: 20px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 10px; }
  .recommendations li { font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.6; color: var(--color-text-body); }
</style>
